english:
  title: Rising Late Due to Wine
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A sick man is like a sick ox or horse,
    Chewing grass, drinking water, freed from all labor.
    Though I lie abed without rising, who can blame me?
    Only when the sun is high do I see food and lift my head.

    White clouds lodged at my roof last night,
    By morning already turned to rain upon the western hills.
    The poet too shared wine with the night,
    Yet at dawn's drum he rode off to court.

    The world keeps ledgers bound by stone and scale—
    Walls full of books and verse I do not read.
    My household mocks the grime upon my skin,
    The servants grumble that I eat so late.
    All laugh because my illness bars me from office,
    But I am blessed: through sickness have found leisure.

    Now I understand: preference and aversion shift like clouds—
    Who else in this life loves sickness as I do?
    My nature runs counter to the world's ways,
    Where others retreat, I turn my face.
    These eyes have always preferred to see alone,
    This mouth loves candor, though it oft offends.

    Heaven pitied my great error, it seems,
    And twisted my mouth, crossed my eyes.
    For five months now behind closed doors I've lain—
    No fame to lose, no one to curse my name.
    But if my mouth and eyes should straighten again,
    I fear my body will rush, and troubles multiply.
